04638nam a22005295i 9780226318806DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015009033  a97802263188067 a10.7208/97802263188062doi  a(DE-B1597)550272  a(OCoLC)1229161462  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHG6024.A3bA67 2016 4aHG6024.A3 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a332.64/57014  aQC 0102rvk0(DE-625)rvk/141236:1 aAppadurai, Arjun, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBanking on Words :bThe Failure of Language in the Age of Derivative Finance /cArjun Appadurai. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tCHAPTER ONE. THE LOGIC OF PROMISSORY FINANCE -- tCHAPTER TWO. THE ENTREPRENEURIAL ETHIC AND THE SPIRIT OF FINANCIALISM -- tCHAPTER THREE. THE GHOST IN THE FINANCIAL MACHINE -- tCHAPTER FOUR. THE SACRED MARKET -- tCHAPTER FIVE. SOCIALITY, UNCERTAINTY, AND RITUAL -- tCHAPTER SIX. THE CHARISMATIC DERIVATIVE -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. THE WEALTH OF DIVIDUALS -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. THE GLOBAL AMBITIONS OF FINANCE -- tCHAPTER NINE. THE END OF THE CONTRACTUAL PROMISE -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this provocative look at one of the most important events of our time, renowned scholar Arjun Appadurai argues that the economic collapse of 2008—while indeed spurred on by greed, ignorance, weak regulation, and irresponsible risk-taking—was, ultimately, a failure of language. To prove this sophisticated point, he takes us into the world of derivative finance, which has become the core of contemporary trading and the primary target of blame for the collapse and all our subsequent woes. With incisive argumentation, he analyzes this challengingly technical world, drawing on thinkers such as J. L. Austin, Marcel Mauss, and Max Weber as theoretical guides to showcase the ways language—and particular failures in it—paved the way for ruin. Appadurai moves in four steps through his analysis. In the first, he highlights the importance of derivatives in contemporary finance, isolating them as the core technical innovation that markets have produced. In the second, he shows that derivatives are essentially written contracts about the future prices of assets—they are, crucially, a promise. Drawing on Mauss’s The Gift and Austin’s theories on linguistic performatives, Appadurai, in his third step, shows how the derivative exploits the linguistic power of the promise through the special form that money takes in finance as the most abstract form of commodity value. Finally, he pinpoints one crucial feature of derivatives (as seen in the housing market especially): that they can make promises that other promises will be broken. He then details how this feature spread contagiously through the market, snowballing into the systemic liquidity crisis that we are all too familiar with now. With his characteristic clarity, Appadurai explains one of the most complicated—and yet absolutely central—aspects of our modern economy. He makes the critical link we have long needed to make: between the numerical force of money and the linguistic force of what we say we will do with it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDerivative securitiesxSocial aspects. 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226318806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226318806.jpg  a978-3-